# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sercos
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sercos/industrial-ethernet] Industrial Ethernet can also refer to the use of standard Ethernet protocols with rugged connectors and extended temperature switches in an industrial environment, for automation or process control.
[src:sercos/industrial-ethernet] Components used in plant process areas must be designed to work in harsh environments of temperature extremes, humidity, and vibration that exceed the ranges for information technology equipment intended for installation in controlled environments.
[src:sercos/industrial-ethernet] The use of fiber-optic Ethernet variants reduces the problems of electrical noise and provides electrical isolation.
[src:sercos/industrial-ethernet] Some industrial networks emphasized deterministic delivery of transmitted data, whereas Ethernet used collision detection which made transport time for individual data packets difficult to estimate with increasing network traffic.
[src:sercos/industrial-ethernet] Typically, industrial uses of Ethernet employ full-duplex standards and other methods so that collisions do not unacceptably influence transmission times.
[src:sercos/industrial-ethernet] Industrial use requires consideration of the environment in which the equipment must operate.
[src:sercos/industrial-ethernet] Factory equipment must tolerate a wider range of temperature, vibration, physical contamination and electrical noise than equipment installed in dedicated information-technology wiring closets.
[src:sercos/industrial-ethernet] Since critical process control may rely on an Ethernet link, the economic cost of interruptions may be high and high availability is therefore an essential criterion.
[src:sercos/industrial-ethernet] Industrial Ethernet networks must interoperate with both current and legacy systems, and must provide predictable performance and maintainability.
[src:sercos/industrial-ethernet] In addition to physical compatibility and low-level transport protocols, a practical industrial Ethernet system must also provide interoperability of higher levels of the OSI model.
[src:sercos/industrial-ethernet] An industrial network must provide security both from intrusions from outside the plant, and inadvertent or unauthorized use within the plant.
[src:sercos/industrial-ethernet] When an industrial network must connect to an office network or external networks, a firewall system can be inserted to control exchange of data between the networks.
[src:sercos/industrial-ethernet] This network separation preserves the performance and reliability of the industrial network.
[src:sercos/industrial-ethernet] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) communicate using one of several possible open or proprietary protocols, such as EtherNet/IP, EtherCAT, Modbus, Sinec H1, Profibus, CANopen, DeviceNet or FOUNDATION Fieldbus.
[src:sercos/industrial-ethernet] The idea to use standard Ethernet makes these systems more interoperable.
[src:sercos/motion-control] Typically the position or velocity of machines are controlled using some type of device such as a hydraulic pump, linear actuator, or electric motor, generally a servo.
[src:sercos/motion-control] Motion control is an important part of robotics and CNC machine tools, however in these instances it is more complex than when used with specialized machines, where the kinematics are usually simpler.
[src:sercos/motion-control] The latter is often called General Motion Control (GMC).
[src:sercos/motion-control] Motion control is widely used in the packaging, printing, textile, semiconductor production, and assembly industries.
[src:sercos/motion-control] Motion Control encompasses every technology related to the movement of objects.
[src:sercos/motion-control] It covers every motion system from micro-sized systems such as silicon-type micro induction actuators to micro-siml systems such as a space platform.
[src:sercos/motion-control] But, these days, the focus of motion control is the special control technology of motion systems with electric actuators such as dc/ac servo motors.
[src:sercos/motion-control] Control of robotic manipulators is also included in the field of motion control because most of robotic manipulators are driven by electrical servo motors and the key objective is the control of motion.
[src:sercos/motion-control] The interface between the motion controller and drives it control is very critical when coordinated motion is required, as it must provide tight synchronization.
[src:sercos/motion-control] Historically the only open interface was an analog signal, until open interfaces were developed that satisfied the requirements of coordinated motion control, the first being SERCOS in 1991 which is now enhanced to SERCOS III.
[src:sercos/motion-control] Later interfaces capable of motion control include Ethernet/IP, Profinet IRT, Ethernet Powerlink, and EtherCAT.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is also used in simulation to mean that the simulation's clock runs at the same speed as a real clock.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Real-time responses are often understood to be in the order of milliseconds, and sometimes microseconds.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] A system not specified as operating in real time cannot usually *guarantee* a response within any timeframe, although *typical* or *expected* response times may be given.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Real-time processing *fails* if not completed within a specified deadline relative to an event; deadlines must always be met, regardless of system load.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] A real-time system has been described as one which "controls an environment by receiving data, processing them, and returning the results sufficiently quickly to affect the environment at that time".
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is used in process control and enterprise systems to mean "without significant delay".
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Real-time software may use one or more of the following: synchronous programming languages, real-time operating systems (RTOSes), and real-time networks.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Each of these provides essential frameworks on which to build a real-time software application.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Systems used for many safety-critical applications must be real-time, such as for control of fly-by-wire aircraft, or anti-lock brakes, both of which demand immediate and accurate mechanical response.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] The term *real-time* derives from its use in early simulation, where a real-world process is simulated at a rate which matched that of the real process (now called real-time simulation to avoid ambiguity).
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Analog computers, most often, were capable of simulating at a much faster pace than real-time, a situation that could be just as dangerous as a slow simulation if it were not also recognized and accounted for.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Minicomputers, particularly from the 1970s onwards, when built into dedicated embedded systems such as DOG (digital on-screen graphic) scanners, increased the need for low-latency priority-driven responses to important interactions with incoming data.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Operating systems such as Data General's RDOS (Real-Time Disk Operating System) and RTOS with background and foreground scheduling as well as Digital Equipment Corporation's RT-11 date from this era.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Background-foreground scheduling allowed low-priority tasks CPU time when no foreground task needed to execute, and gave absolute priority within the foreground to threads/tasks with the highest priority.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Real-time operating systems would also be used for time-sharing multiuser duties.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] For example, Data General Business Basic could run in the foreground or background of RDOS and would introduce additional elements to the scheduling algorithm to make it more appropriate for people interacting via dumb terminals.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Early personal computers were sometimes used for real-time computing.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] The possibility of deactivating other interrupts allowed for hard-coded loops with defined timing, and the low interrupt latency allowed the implementation of a real-time operating system, giving the user interface and the disk drives lower priority than the real-time thread.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] However, several coding libraries exist that offer real-time capabilities in a high-level language on a variety of operating systems, for example, Real-time Java.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Later microprocessors such as the Motorola 68000 and subsequent family members (68010, 68020, ColdFire, etc.) also became popular with manufacturers of industrial control systems.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] This application area is one where real-time control offers genuine advantages in terms of process performance and safety.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] A system is said to be *real-time* if the total correctness of an operation depends not only upon its logical correctness, but also upon the time in which it is performed.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Thus, the goal of a *hard real-time system* is to ensure that all deadlines are met, but for *soft real-time systems* the goal becomes meeting a certain subset of deadlines in order to optimize some application-specific criteria.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] The particular criteria optimized depend on the application, but some typical examples include maximizing the number of deadlines met, minimizing the lateness of tasks and maximizing the number of high-priority tasks meeting their deadlines.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] In the context of multitasking systems the scheduling policy is normally priority driven (pre-emptive schedulers).
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] In some situations, these can guarantee hard real-time performance (for instance, if the set of tasks and their priorities is known in advance).
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] There are other hard real-time schedulers such as rate-monotonic, which is not common in general-purpose systems, as it requires additional information in order to schedule a task: namely, a bound or worst-case estimate for how long the task must execute.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Specific algorithms for scheduling such hard real-time tasks exist, like earliest deadline first, which, ignoring the overhead of context switching, is sufficient for system loads of less than 100%.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] New overlay scheduling systems, such as an adaptive partition scheduler assist in managing large systems with a mixture of hard real-time and non real-time applications.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] In a real-time digital signal processing (DSP) process, the analyzed (input) and generated (output) samples can be processed (or generated) continuously in the time it takes to input and output the same set of samples *independent* of the processing delay.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] It means that the processing delay must be bounded even if the processing continues for an unlimited time.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] The mean processing time per sample, including overhead, is no greater than the sampling period, which is the reciprocal of the sampling rate.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] This is the criterion whether the samples are grouped together in large segments and processed as blocks or are processed individually and whether there are long, short, or non-existent input and output buffers.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Consider an audio DSP example; if a process requires 2.01 seconds to analyze, synthesize, or process 2.00 seconds of sound, it is not real-time.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] However, if it takes 1.99 seconds, it is or can be made into a real-time DSP process.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] A common life analogy is standing in a line or queue waiting for the checkout in a grocery store.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] If the line asymptotically grows longer and longer without bound, the checkout process is not real-time.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] If the length of the line is bounded, customers are being "processed" and output as rapidly, on average, as they are being inputted, then that process *is* real-time.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] The grocer might go out of business or must at least lose business if they cannot make their checkout process real-time; thus, it is fundamentally important that this process is real-time.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] A signal processing algorithm that cannot keep up with the flow of input data, with output falling further and further behind the input, is not real-time.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] If the delay of the output (relative to the input) is bounded regarding a process that operates over an unlimited time, then that signal processing algorithm is real-time, even if the throughput delay may be very long.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Real-time signal processing is necessary, but not sufficient in and of itself, for live signal processing such as what is required in live event support.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Live audio digital signal processing requires both real-time operation and a sufficient limit to throughput delay so as to be tolerable to performers using stage monitors or in-ear monitors and not noticeable as lip sync error by the audience also directly watching the performers.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Tolerable limits to latency for live, real-time processing is a subject of investigation and debate, but is estimated to be between 6 and 20 milliseconds.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Real-time bidirectional telecommunications delays of less than 300 ms ("round trip" or twice the unidirectional delay) are considered "acceptable" to avoid undesired "talk-over" in conversation.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Real-time computing is sometimes misunderstood to be high-performance computing, but this is not an accurate classification.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] For example, a massive supercomputer executing a scientific simulation may offer impressive performance, yet it is not executing a real-time computation.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Conversely, once the hardware and software for an anti-lock braking system have been designed to meet its required deadlines, no further performance gains are obligatory or even useful.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Furthermore, if a network server is highly loaded with network traffic, its response time may be slower, but will (in most cases) still succeed before it times out (hits its deadline).
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Hence, such a network server would not be considered a real-time system: temporal failures (delays, time-outs, etc.) are typically small and compartmentalized (limited in effect), but are not catastrophic failures.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] In a real-time system, such as the FTSE 100 Index, a slowdown beyond limits would often be considered catastrophic in its application context.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] The most important requirement of a real-time system is consistent output, not high throughput.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Some kinds of software, such as many chess-playing programs, can fall into either category.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] For instance, a chess program designed to play in a tournament with a clock will need to decide on a move before a certain deadline or lose the game, and is therefore a real-time computation, but a chess program that is allowed to run indefinitely before moving is not.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] In both of these cases, however, high performance is desirable: the more work a tournament chess program can do in the allotted time, the better its moves will be, and the faster an unconstrained chess program runs, the sooner it will be able to move.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] High performance is indicative of the amount of processing that is performed in a given amount of time, whereas real-time is the ability to get done with the processing to yield a useful output in the available time.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] For example, a near-real-time display depicts an event or situation as it existed at the current time minus the processing time, as nearly the time of the live event.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] The distinction between the terms "near real time" and "real time" is somewhat nebulous and must be defined for the situation at hand.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] The term implies that there are no significant delays.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] In many cases, processing described as "real-time" would be more accurately described as "near real-time".
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Near real-time also refers to delayed real-time transmission of voice and video.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] It allows playing video images, in approximately real-time, without having to wait for an entire large video file to download.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Incompatible databases can export/import to common flat files that the other database can import/export on a scheduled basis so they can sync/share common data in "near real-time" with each other.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Several methods exist to aid the design of real-time systems, an example of which is MASCOT, an old but very successful method that represents the concurrent structure of the system.
[src:sercos/real-time-computing] Other examples are HOOD, Real-Time UML, AADL, the Ravenscar profile, and Real-time Java.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] To achieve the throughput and jitter requirements in Sercos applications, Sercos III operates primarily in a Master/Slave arrangement exchanging cyclic data between nodes.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The master initiates all data transmission during a Sercos real-time cycle.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] All data transmissions begin and end at the master (circular).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Communication across a Sercos III network occurs in strict cyclic intervals.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] A cycle time is chosen by the user for a given application, ranging from 31.25 μs to 65 ms.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Within each cycle, data is exchanged between Sercos III nodes using two types of telegrams: MDTs and ATs (see Telegram Types).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] After all MDTs and ATs are transmitted, Sercos III nodes allow the remaining time in the cycle to be used as an UC (Unified Communication) Channel, which can be used to exchange data using other formats, such as IP.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The network remains available to UCC traffic until the next cycle begins, at which time Sercos III closes the nodes to UCC traffic again.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Sercos is purposely designed to provide open access at all ports for other protocols between cyclic real-time messages.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] This provides the advantage that any Sercos III node is available, whether Sercos III is in cyclic mode or not, to use other protocols, such as TCP/IP, without any additional hardware to process tunneling.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Sercos nodes are specified to provide a store and forward method of buffering non-Sercos messages should they be received at a node while cyclic communication is active.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] All Sercos III telegrams conform to the IEEE 802.3 and ISO/IEC 8802-3 MAC (media access control) frame format.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] This is because all telegrams are issued by the master, and are intended for all slaves on the network.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] of the master, as it issues all telegrams.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Field Registration Authority for Sercos III (0x88CD).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The beginning of an Ethernet-defined data field always begins with a Sercos III header, which contains control and status information unique to Sercos.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The Sercos III header is followed by the Sercos III data field, which contains a configurable set of variables defined for each device in the network.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Two main types of telegrams are used within the Sercos III Cycle.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The Master Data Telegram (MDT) and the Acknowledge Telegram (AT).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Both telegram types are issued by the master (control).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The MDT contains information provided by the master to other devices.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] It is filled by the master and read by other devices.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The AT is issued by the master but is populated by each other device with appropriate response data (feedback values, input states, etc.).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] More than one device uses the same AT, filling in its pre-determined area in the AT telegram, updating checksums, and then passing the telegram to the next device.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] This method reduces the Ethernet frame overhead's impact on the network's performance without compromising IEEE 802.3 and ISO/IEC 8802-3.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The amount of data sent from the master to other devices and the sum of the data returned by the other devices may exceed the 802.3-specified maximum 1500-byte data field size.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] To comply with this limit, Sercos III may use more than one MDT telegram in a cycle and more than one AT telegram (up to 4 in each case).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] To achieve true hard real-time characteristics, Sercos III, like Sercos I and II, uses a form of synchronization that depends upon a synchronization “mark” issued by the master control at exact equidistant time intervals.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] All nodes in a Sercos network use this telegram to synchronize all activities in the node.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] To account for variations in network components, delays are measured in the node-to-node transmissions during the phase-up (initialization) of a Sercos network, and those values are compensated for during normal operation.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Unlike Sercos I and II, where a separate Master Sync Telegram, or MST is used for this purpose, Sercos III includes the MST in the first MDT transmitted.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The time between two MSTs is exactly equal to the designated Sercos cycle time, Stacy.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The synchronization process ensures that cyclical and simultaneous synchronization of all connected devices occurs independently of topology and the number of devices in Sercos networks.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Sercos III supports standard IEEE 802.3 and ISO/IEC 8802-3 100BASE-TX or 100BASE-FX (100 Mbit/s baseband) full duplex physical layer (PHY) entities.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] 802.3-compliant Media-Access Controller (MAC) sub-layers are used.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Auto-negotiation must be enabled on each PHY, but only 100 Mbit full duplex is supported.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Auto (MAU [Media Attachment Unit]-Embedded) Crossover is specified between the two Physical Medium Attachment (PMA) units present with a duplex port.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] These two units are referred to as the Primary Channel and Secondary Channel in the Sercos III specification.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Dual interfaces are required (two duplex interfaces per device).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Within the Sercos III specification, the dual interfaces are referred to as P1 and P2 (Ports 1 and 2).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Every Ethernet and IP protocol on Sercos devices can be accessed without interfering with the real-time protocol and without requiring the real-time operation to be activated.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] All of the functionality required to configure a Sercos III interface is contained in a stack that is available in both “hard” and “soft” versions.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The hardware stack is available in several different forms.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The maximum jitter allowed with hard-stack-based masters and slaves is less than 1 μs.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Using the above stacks yields a jitter similar to Sercos II (35-70 nanoseconds).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Sercos III also supports an operating system and hardware platform independent “Soft Master”, using a completely software-based stack for the master interface.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Since the maximum jitter in such a configuration is dependent upon the operating system of the Master, the maximum jitter may be set by a variable for the Sercos III network when a Soft Master is employed.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] A standard Ethernet controller can be used for applications with line topology, bus cycle times greater than 500 us, and microsecond range synchronization.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Applications with higher synchronization requirements and lower bus cycle times can be implemented using a TTS-capable Ethernet controller with a suitable real-time operating system.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] For basic Slaves, such as I/O devices, EasySlave-IO, a license-free bitstream variant of the EasySlave is available.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] A product that uses an Arduino board as a rapid prototype platform for an application, plus a corresponding shield (add-on module) with a Sercos EasySlave FPGA, plus other peripheral components, is available.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] A term usually associated with the IT enterprise, data consistency can also apply to real-time control (see for example Peer to Peer Communication).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] For this reason, Sercos III specifies that no data be overwritten (destroyed) during a transmission.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Every slave on a network may access input and output data for every other slave on the network.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Devices must support Ethernet's MAC addressing, plus the Sercos III addressing.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Each Sercos III device contains a numeric address used by other devices on the Sercos III network to exchange data.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The address may be any whole integer from 1 to 511.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Sercos III does not use an IP address for its operation.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The Sercos III specification defines two possible network topologies; Ring and Line.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] To those familiar with other networks, both of them may appear to be configured as a ring.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] All telegrams begin and end at the master.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The Full Duplex feature of the physical layer is used to achieve this.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] A line topology is the simplest of the two possible arrangements and provides no redundancy.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] However, this configuration saves the cost of one cable.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] In it, only one of the two interfaces on the master is used.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Telegrams are issued out of the transmit PMA on the Master’s active port.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Either port on the master may be the active one.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Sercos III determines this during phase-up (initialization).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The first slave receives the telegrams on the connected interface's receive PMA, modifies them as required, and issues them out on the transmit PMA of the second interface.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Each cascading Slave does likewise until the last Slave in the Line is reached.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] That slave, detecting no Sercos III connection on its second port, folds the telegram back on the receiving interface's transmit port.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The telegram then makes its way through each Slave back to the Master.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Note the last slave also emits all Sercos III telegrams on its second port, even though no Sercos III connection is detected.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] This is for snooping, ring closures (see below), and hot-plugging.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Keep in mind that since the Ethernet destination field in all Sercos III telegrams is the broadcast address of 0xFFFF FFFF FFFF (all 1s), all telegrams issued from this open port will be seen by other devices as broadcast telegrams.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] This behavior is by design, and cannot be disabled.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] To avoid taxing networks attached to an open Sercos port, an IP-Switch can be used, or alternately a managed Ethernet switch programmed to block broadcast telegrams received from the Sercos port can be used.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Starting with Sercos III specification version 1.3.1 the connection of industrial Ethernet devices is supported where devices work with 20 ms cycle time in communication phase 0 (CP 0).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] A ring topology simply closes the network by attaching the unused port on the last device in a ring back to the unused port on the Master.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] When the Sercos III Master senses that a ring exists, it sets up two counter-rotating telegrams.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The same data is issued simultaneously out of the transmit PMAs of both ports on the Master.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] From there both telegrams are managed essentially identically as they make their way through each Slave, ending back at the opposite port on the Master they were emitted from.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Advantages to this topology include tighter synchronization, as well as automatic infrastructure redundancy (see below).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Sercos III operates in a “circular” approach with both the line or ring structure.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] All telegrams leave the master and return.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] As with any network that operates in this manner, modified structures can be constructed to appear as a tree or star network, utilizing hardware that manages the branches, but the structure is still circular.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Sercos III is designed in such a way that no additional network infrastructure (standard Ethernet switches, Hubs, etc.) is required to operate.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Normal standard Ethernet (non-Sercos III capable) components may be placed within a Sercos III network, as their presence will not adversely affect the timing and synchronization of the network.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Guarantee synchronization in extended networks using media converters requires Cut-through switching.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] If ring redundancy shall be achieved, Link Loss Forwarding with appropriate reaction times is necessary.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] A variety of products is available that enable the connection of field buses (Profibus and CAN) or sensor/actuator buses (AS-i, SSI, IO-Link) to a Sercos network.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Gateways are available to integrate analog axes.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Gateways are incorporated into Sercos devices (e.g., modular I/Os) or are connected as separate components in the network.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The Sercos III specification defines a broad range of variables developed by a consortium of product suppliers to provide interoperability between components (motion controls, drives, etc.).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] All traffic across a Sercos III network consists of Idents (parameters) with attributes.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The idents define over 700 standardized parameters that describe the interaction between electric, pneumatic, and hydraulic control systems, drives, and other peripheral devices using universal semantics.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] This method was first defined in Sercos I, as an essentially flat set of idents.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] They were later grouped into application sets to aid in the selection of pertinent incidents required for a given industry, such as the “Pack Profile” for use with packaging machinery.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] During the development of the Sercos III specification, this methodology was further refined to group the incidents logically by device class.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The definition of the legacy idents has remained largely untouched; rather their grouping has been re-evaluated for a more understandable architecture.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] This has also enabled the separation of communication idents into a logical subset, simplifying migration from Sercos I/II to Sercos III, and providing a clear overview to users.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] When a ring network is employed, Sercos III provides for automatic infrastructure redundancy.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] If any interconnection point in the ring ceases to function, the associated Sercos III nodes will detect a “ring break” and “loop back” the end nodes, effectively operating as two lines rather than one ring.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The operation is “bump-less”, as the detection and recovery time for such a break is less than 25 μs, which is less than the minimum Sercos III cycle time.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Sercos III can also recover from ring breaks and “heal” with no interruption in operation.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] To ensure the determinism required, most real-time Ethernet standards enforce a master-to-slave-only method of communications.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] This can conflict with the need for a node in the system to exchange data efficiently with a node other than the network master.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The conventional method to achieve this in a master-slave network is to pass data from one slave node to the master, where it is reissued to one or more different slaves.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] For example, if several servo drives on a network are to be synchronized to a signal from another drive on the network, the master must fetch the signal from this drive and reissue it to all other drives on the network.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Disadvantages to this method are that delays are induced due to the multiple cycles required, and the master's processing load is increased as it must actively participate in the function, although it contributes nothing.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Since no data is destroyed in a Sercos III telegram, data to and from any slave can be accessed by another node on the network without any additional cycle delay or master intervention.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Additionally, as telegrams pass each node twice in a cycle (for both topology types), a node can even have the opportunity to access data supplied by a subsequent node.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Two peer communication methods are defined in the Sercos III specification: Controller to Controller (C2C) for multiple masters to communicate with one another, and Cross Communication (CC) for multiple slaves.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Another feature of Sercos III is hot-plugging, which is the ability to add devices to an active network.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Using the features described for redundancy, a network can detect when a new device is attached to an active network.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Processes exist that configure the new device, and announce its availability to the master control.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] After that, the master control can select to make use of the new device based on the application currently running.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Oversampling allows more than one nominal/actual value to be transmitted per cycle, increasing the delicate nature of process control in extremely critical applications, such as laser applications.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Time stamping transmits event-controlled results, such as specific measured data, and switches outputs independently from the cycle.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] This increases the stability of the process in complex processing solutions, such as those in the semiconductor industry.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The time between the end of the transmission of all Sercos III Real Time (RT) cyclic telegrams and the beginning of the next communication cycle is defined as the “Sercos III Unified Communication Channel” (UC Channel).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] During this period, the Sercos network is opened to allow transmission of Ethernet-compliant frames for other services and protocols.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Frames from other Fieldbus standards that conform to Ethernet frame formatting may be transmitted across a Sercos III network.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Every Sercos III-compliant node must support the passing of UC frames through its Sercos III interface.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Whether a Sercos III node actively uses the UC feature is determined by the product's feature set.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] If, for example, the device has an embedded web server, it could make available its IP address for access by other devices.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] A Sercos III network will always pass UC frames, even when the cyclic operation has not been initialized.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] This means that devices always have access to the network for UC messages, as long as the ports are powered.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Sercos III does not define whether a port should operate in cut-through switching or store-and-forward mode when handling UC frames.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] There are Sercos III products currently on the market that support both modes.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Likewise, Sercos III does not define whether a port should intelligently process UC telegrams, such as learning the network topology.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The time allotted for UC traffic is dictated by the amount of data transmitted during the real-time portion of the cycle.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] In real-world applications, there is a significant amount of bandwidth available for UC frames.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] For example, in a typical application with 8 axes of motion and a cycle rate of 250 μs, the equivalent of 85 Mbit/s is available for UC use.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] This amount of time means the UC frames in this example can be as long as the maximum defined for Ethernet (Maximum Transmission Unit [MTU] =1500).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Using the same example of 8 axes but with a cycle time of 62.5 μs, the effective bandwidth available for UC frames would be 40 Mbit/s and the MTU would be reduced to 325.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] As with any network where time on the bus is shared, MTU values should be configured to ensure reliable communication.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Properly configured Sercos networks will set the Sercos parameter “Requested MTU” (S-0-1027.0.1) to the recommended MTU value, which can then be read by other devices to match their MTU settings.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Regardless of the value of this parameter, a Sercos node will allow non-Sercos traffic to pass for the entire UC channel period (i.e., telegrams longer than the MTU setting are not discarded by the Sercos stack).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Sercos parameter S-0-1027.0.1 is set by default to 576, the minimum value called out in RFC 791.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] UC frames may only enter a Sercos III network through a Sercos III-compliant port.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] This can be achieved in two different ways.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] One is to employ the unused Sercos III port at the end of a Sercos III network configured in line topology, as shown to the right.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] In a network configured in a ring topology, the ring can be temporarily broken at any point to also attach a device.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Since the redundancy feature of Sercos III will reconfigure the network in a bump-less manner (responding in less than one cycle), no disruption of network transmission will occur.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The ring can again be closed after the access is no longer required.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] IP-Switches supply two Sercos III-compliant ports, and one or more ports for UCC access.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Commercially available UCC Switches block the transmission of Sercos III broadcast telegrams out their non-Sercos III port(s), to prevent flooding of non-Sercos III networks with Sercos III cyclic data.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Sercos III is designed so that EtherNet/IP.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] TC/IP and Sercos devices can operate over the same Ethernet cable.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The high-efficiency Sercos telegrams use only a portion of the existing bandwidth, allowing non-Sercos telegrams to be transmitted via the UC channel.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] A Sercos master and an EtherNet/IP scanner are required to implement a common network infrastructure.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] They can be combined into a dual-stack master.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Where redundancy is not necessary, the devices are connected in a line topology, where the last Sercos device in the line transmits and receives non-Sercos telegrams via its free port.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] A free port is not available when the network is configured in a ring topology for redundant data communication.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] In such a configuration, an IP switch is required to allow non-Sercos packets into the ring.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] "Functional safety" is a general term referring to the design of a system that reduces the risk that a hazardous event harmful to humans can occur with a system.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The main definition is contained in the international standard IEC 61508.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Most industrial networks contain some type of features to conform to functional safety requirements.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Rather than define a unique specification for this functional safety, Sercos III Safety is based upon the CIP Safety protocol developed by the Open DeviceNet Vendors Association (ODVA).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] This provides interoperability at the safety level with all networks based upon the Common Industry Protocol (CIP), including DeviceNet and EtherNet/IP.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] CIP Safety on Sercos provides for safe data transmission over Sercos III up to SIL 3 (Safety Integrity Level).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] No additional safety bus is required, as the safety information is sent in addition to the standard data on the Sercos network.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] With CIP Safety on Sercos, data is sent on the same medium using the same connections as standard communication.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The function of the cross-media CIP Safety protocol is performed by the end units, making it possible to simultaneously operate standard and safety devices in the same network.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Reliable communication can take place between all network levels, including peer-to-peer communication and cross-network communication.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The master does not necessarily have to be a safety controller.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] It can also route data without being able to interpret it.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] This makes it possible to configure the safety network architecture for the implementation of safety programmable controllers or peer-to-peer communication between sensors and actuators.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The Sercos I/O profile is a device profile for decentralized I/O modules, which can be used for block and modular I/Os.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] It also supports hybrid devices that combine several functionalities in one single device, e.g., a two-axis controller with I/O and master functionality.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] An XML-based device and profile description language is specified for I/O device configuration.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] SDDML (Sercos Device Description Markup Language) describes which profiles are supported by a certain device.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] SPDML (Sercos Profile Description Markup Language) is used to specify the different profiles based on the Sercos parameter model.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Existing standard parameters can be used and manufacturer-specific parameters can also be defined.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Sercos Energy is an application layer profile that defines parameters and commands for the reduction of energy consumption in a uniform vendor-independent manner.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Energy is saved during processing by switching off components that are not required at a particular time or point in the process (partial machine operation).
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] In operation, the control reads out the parameters of each Sercos Energy component via the Sercos III network, receiving status information and detailed consumption values.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The profile considers energy-saving conditions for predictable breaks such as lunch periods and plant holidays.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] At pre-defined times, Sercos Energy components are brought into a standstill condition to save energy.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Shortly before the end of the interruption, Sercos Energy provides for the re-initialization of components in stand-by condition, to make them available again.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Sercos Energy provides mechanisms for unintended breaks caused by machine errors and missing parts.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] In these situations, target components can be carefully brought into energy-saving modes while errors are being fixed or during a wait for new parts.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] By using intelligent controls, axes, and components that are unneeded in ongoing production processes can be switched off, and/or target completion times can be adjusted, while still achieving full productivity.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The function-specific Encoder Profile ensures that encoders from different manufacturers can be utilized in Sercos applications without compatibility problems.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Supported encoder functions are defined, and their use with other devices, e.g., controls, is specified.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Both stand-alone encoders and hybrid devices with encoders are supported.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The OPC Foundation and Sercos International developed an OPC UA companion specification which describes the mapping of Sercos to OPC UA.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] This makes the functions and parameters of Sercos III devices available to OPC UA, independent of any vendor.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] This simplifies communication between machine automation devices and higher-level supervisory systems.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The multi-protocol capabilities of Sercos III allow various implementation options.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] The OPC UA server functionality can be implemented into machine control or directly into a Sercos field device, such as a drive, sensor, or I/O module.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] An OPC client can also be integrated into a Sercos controller.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] An OPC client and OPC UA server can communicate with each other even when Sercos real-time communication is not active, because the Sercos transmission process does not require tunneling.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] I/O Link is a digital interface for the connection of sensors and actuators to higher-level automation busses, such as Sercos III.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] An IO-Link master can be either a stand-alone slave or part of a modular slave device.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] An IO-Link-to-Sercos mapping guide is available to assist manufacturers in integrating IO-Link into a Sercos III network.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] An IO-Link development board with an IO-Link master and a Sercos III slave interface is available.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] AS-i (Actuator Sensor Interface) is a networking interface for the connection of simple field devices such as actuators and sensors to higher-level busses, such as Sercos III.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Several AS-i/Sercos gateways are available for connection of AS-i devices to a Sercos III network.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Standard Ethernet is not deterministic and, therefore not suitable for hard real-time communications.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] To address that problem, the Time-Sensitive Networking task group of the IEEE 802.1 working group is developing a set of standards that define mechanisms for hard real-time data transmission over Ethernet networks.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] A Sercos working group has determined that Sercos is compatible with TSN.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] A Sercos TSN demonstrator was developed to illustrate the real-time multi-protocol capable Sercos network based on TSN.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Driver software is used to connect a controller to the device logic.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Several basic Sercos drivers are available as open-source software from sourceforge.net.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] These include a common Sercos Master API library, Sercos Internet Protocol Services software and a Sercos UCC Ethernet network driver.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] An open-source Sercos SoftMaster is also available from sourceforge.net.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] It emulates the Sercos functions so that a standard Ethernet controller can be used instead of FPGA or ASIC hardware.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] A pre-certified CIP Safety on Sercos protocol software is available to equip Sercos and EtherNet/IP devices with the appropriate safe logic up to SIL3.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Conformance testing verifies that both controls and peripheral devices comply with Sercos standards and can operate interoperably in networks with products from multiple vendors.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] A testing tool, The Sercos Conformizer, can be used to subject a device to a pre-test before the formal conformance procedure.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Sercos International e.V., a Sercos user's group headquartered in Germany, developed and supports Sercos as an open IEC standard, independent of any individual company.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Sercos also has user groups in North America and Asia.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Membership in a Sercos user's group is voluntary.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Experts from both member and non-member companies actively contribute to the further development and support of Sercos via engineering working groups, considering market trends plus input from Sercos vendors regarding practical field applications.
[src:sercos/sercos-iii] Sercos International is a recognized partner of the Industrial Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) and actively contributes to the IEC standards for machine automation.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] In the field of Industrial Control Systems, the interfacing of various control components must provide means to coordinate the signals and commands sent between control modules.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] While tight coordination is desirable for discrete inputs and outputs, it is especially important in motion controls, where directing the movement of individual axes of motion must be precisely coordinated so that the motion of the entire system follows a desired path.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] Types of equipment requiring such coordination include metal cutting machine tools, metal forming equipment, assembly machinery, packaging machinery, robotics, printing machinery and material handling equipment.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] The **Sercos** (**se**rial **r**eal-time **co**mmunication **s**ystem) interface is a globally standardized open digital interface for the communication between industrial controls, motion devices (drives) and input output devices (I/O).
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] Sercos I and II are standardized in IEC 61491 and EN 61491.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] Sercos is designed to provide hard real-time, high performance communications between industrial motion controls and digital servo drives.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] Until the early 1980s the majority of servo drive systems used to control motion in industrial machinery were based upon analog electronics.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] The accepted interface to control such devices was an analog voltage signal, where polarity represented the desired direction of motion, and magnitude represented the desired speed or torque.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] In the 1980s, drive systems and devices based on digital technology began to emerge.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] A new method needed to be devised to communicate with, and control such units, as their capabilities could not be exploited with the traditional interface method used with analog drives.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] The earliest interfaces were either proprietary to one vendor or designed only for a single purpose, making it difficult for users of motion control systems to freely interchange motion control and drives.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] The membership of the VDW (German Machine Tool Builders' Association) became concerned with the implications of this trend.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] In response to that, in 1987 the VDW formed a joint working group with the ZVEI (German Electrical and Electronics Industry Association) to develop an open interface specification appropriate for digital-drive systems.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] The resulting specification, entitled "Sercos (**se**rial **r**eal-time **co**mmunication **s**ystem) interface, was released and later submitted to the IEC, which in 1995 released it as IEC 61491.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] After the release of the original standard, original working group member companies including ABB, AEG, AMK, Robert Bosch, Indramat, and Siemens founded the "Interest Group Sercos" to steward the standard.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] Over the history of Sercos, its capabilities have been enhanced to the point where today it is not only used for motion control systems, but as a universal automation bus.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] Sercos is supported globally by Sercos International e.V.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] Regional support is provided by Sercos North America(USA), Sercos Japan and Sercos China.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] These organizations provide a forum for the continued development of the standard, as well as user support.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] An important aspect of an open, interoperable communications system is rigorous testing of products for adherence to the standard and their ability to operate in networks of products from multiple vendors.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] Sercos International e.V. supports a Conformance Laboratory at the University of Stuttgart's Institute for Control Engineering of Machine Tools and Manufacturing Units (ISW).
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] Products successfully passing conformance testing may display a mark indicating they are conformance tested.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] Conformance-tested Sercos I and II products are publicized in an index of certified products, Sercos I and II.
[src:sercos/sercos-interface] Conformance-tested Sercos III products are publicized in an index of certified products, Sercos III.
[src:sercos/servomotor] A **servomotor** (or **servo motor** or simply **servo**) is a rotary or linear actuator that allows precise control of angular or linear position, velocity, and acceleration in a mechanical system.
[src:sercos/servomotor] It constitutes part of a servomechanism, and consists of a motor coupled to a sensor (for position feedback) and a controller (often a dedicated module designed for servomotors).
[src:sercos/servomotor] Servomotors are not a specific class of motor, although the term *servomotor* is often used to describe a motor suitable for use in a closed-loop control system.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Servomotors are used in robotics, CNC machinery, and automated manufacturing.
[src:sercos/servomotor] NEMA ICS 16 defines several flange mounting patterns and corresponding bolt circles that are defined in millimeters or inches.
[src:sercos/servomotor] A servomotor is a closed-loop servomechanism that uses position feedback (either linear or angular position) to control its motion and final position.
[src:sercos/servomotor] The input to its control is a signal (either analog or digital) representing the desired position of the output shaft.
[src:sercos/servomotor] The motor is paired with a position encoder to provide position feedback (and potentially also speed feedback).
[src:sercos/servomotor] The controller compares the measured position with the desired position to generate an error signal, which when fed back causes the motor to rotate in the direction needed to bring the shaft to the desired position.
[src:sercos/servomotor] The error signal falls to zero as the desired position is approached, stopping the motor.
[src:sercos/servomotor] A simple servomotor uses position-only sensing via a potentiometer and bang-bang control of the motor, which only rotates at full speed or is stopped.
[src:sercos/servomotor] This type of servomotor is not widely used in industrial motion control, but it forms the basis of the cheap servos in radio-controlled models.
[src:sercos/servomotor] More sophisticated servomotors make use of an absolute encoder (a type of rotary encoder) to calculate the shaft's position and infer the speed of the output shaft.
[src:sercos/servomotor] A variable-speed drive is used to control the motor speed.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Both of these enhancements, usually in combination with a PID control algorithm, allow the servomotor to be brought to its commanded position more quickly and more precisely, with less overshooting.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Servomotors are generally used as a high-performance alternative to the stepper motor.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Stepper motors have some inherent ability to control position, as they have built-in output steps.
[src:sercos/servomotor] This often allows them to be used as an open-loop position control, without any feedback encoder, as their drive signal specifies the number of steps of movement to rotate, but for this, the controller needs to 'know' the position of the stepper motor on power up.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Therefore, on the first power-up, the controller will have to activate the stepper motor and turn it to a known position, e.g. until it activates an end limit switch.
[src:sercos/servomotor] This can be observed when switching on an inkjet printer; the controller will move the ink jet carrier to the extreme left and right to establish the end positions.
[src:sercos/servomotor] A servomotor can immediately turn to whatever angle the controller instructs it to, regardless of the initial position at power up, if an absolute encoder is used.
[src:sercos/servomotor] The lack of feedback of a stepper motor limits its performance, as the stepper motor can only drive a load that is well within its capacity, otherwise missed steps under load may lead to positioning errors and the system may have to be restarted or recalibrated.
[src:sercos/servomotor] The encoder and controller of a servomotor are an additional cost, but they optimize the performance of the overall system (for all of speed, power, and accuracy) relative to the capacity of the basic motor.
[src:sercos/servomotor] With larger systems, where a powerful motor represents an increasing proportion of the system cost, servomotors have the advantage.
[src:sercos/servomotor] There has been increasing popularity in closed-loop stepper motors in recent years.
[src:sercos/servomotor] They act like servomotors but have some differences in their software control to get smooth motion.
[src:sercos/servomotor] The main benefit of an open-loop stepper motor is its relatively low cost.
[src:sercos/servomotor] There is also no need to tune the feedback controller on an open-loop stepper system.
[src:sercos/servomotor] The first servomotors were developed with synchros as their encoders.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Much work was done with these systems in the development of radar and anti-aircraft artillery during World War II.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Simple servomotors may use resistive potentiometers as their position encoder.
[src:sercos/servomotor] These are only used at the very simplest and cheapest level and are in close competition with stepper motors.
[src:sercos/servomotor] They suffer from wear and electrical noise in the potentiometer track.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Although it would be possible to electrically differentiate their position signal to obtain a speed signal, PID controllers that can make use of such a speed signal generally warrant a more precise encoder.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Modern servomotors use rotary encoders, either absolute or incremental.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Absolute encoders can determine their position at power-on but are more complicated and expensive.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Incremental encoders are simpler, cheaper, and work at faster speeds.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Incremental systems, like stepper motors, often combine their inherent ability to measure intervals of rotation with a simple zero-position sensor to set their position at start-up.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Instead of servomotors, sometimes a motor with a separate, external linear encoder is used.
[src:sercos/servomotor] These motor + linear encoder systems avoid inaccuracies in the drivetrain between the motor and linear carriage, but their design is made more complicated as they are no longer a pre-packaged factory-made system.
[src:sercos/servomotor] The type of motor is not critical to a servomotor, and different types may be used.
[src:sercos/servomotor] At the simplest, brushed permanent magnet DC motors are used, owing to their simplicity and low cost.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Small industrial servomotors are typically electronically commutated brushless motors.
[src:sercos/servomotor] For large industrial servomotors, AC induction motors are typically used, often with variable frequency drives to allow control of their speed.
[src:sercos/servomotor] For ultimate performance in a compact package, brushless AC motors with permanent magnet fields are used, effectively large versions of Brushless DC electric motors.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Drive modules for servomotors are a standard industrial component.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Their design is a branch of power electronics, usually based on a three-phase MOSFET or IGBT H bridge.
[src:sercos/servomotor] These standard modules accept a single direction and pulse count (rotation distance) as input.
[src:sercos/servomotor] They may also include over-temperature monitoring, over-torque, and stall detection features.
[src:sercos/servomotor] As the encoder type, gearhead ratio, and overall system dynamics are application specific, it is more difficult to produce the overall controller as an off-the-shelf module, and so these are often implemented as part of the main controller.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Most modern servomotors are designed and supplied around a dedicated controller module from the same manufacturer.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Controllers may also be developed around microcontrollers in order to reduce cost for large-volume applications.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Modern industrial servomotor systems employ digital servo drives or amplifiers to regulate current, velocity, and position using feedback loops.
[src:sercos/servomotor] These drives communicate over industrial fieldbuses such as EtherCAT, CANopen, and POWERLINK, allowing coordinated motion among multiple axes.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Manufacturers including ADVANCED Motion Controls, Bosch Rexroth, and Yaskawa have developed such servo-drive families used in robotics, CNC machinery, and automated production equipment.
[src:sercos/servomotor] Integrated servomotors are designed to include the motor, driver, encoder, and associated electronics into a single package.
